    <segment id="1" parent="8" relname="condition">
I think that if the system is able to successfully continue after recovering from an error that doesn&apos;t affect the user,</segment>
    <segment id="8" parent="11" relname="span"> there generally shouldn&apos;t be a message.</segment>
    <segment id="2" parent="9" relname="circumstance"> 
When the user is affected by the error,</segment>
    <segment id="9" parent="12" relname="span"> the message should be helpful.</segment>
    <segment id="3" parent="13" relname="span"> Recently I had someone using Excel that got an error message &quot;Disk full&quot; when he tried to copy a sheet.</segment>
    <segment id="4" parent="3" relname="elaboration"> Obviously he had plenty of disk space and could find nothing that was &quot;full&quot; to cause the error.</segment>
    <segment id="5" parent="14" relname="span"> Searching for help from Microsoft found this was known to happen with Excel</segment>
    <segment id="10" parent="5" relname="elaboration"> and they suggested a work around.</segment>
    <segment id="6" parent="16" relname="span"> The message was unhelpful as to the real problem.</segment>
    <segment id="7" parent="6" relname="elaboration"> It seems many messages are like this.</segment>
